{"title_page": "Bernard Dong Bortey", "text_new": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name= Bernard Bortey\n| image = \n| fullname = Bernard Dong-Bortey\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1982|9|22|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Nungua]], Ghana\n| height = 1.80m<ref>{{FootballDatabase.eu|5678<!-- -bernard-dongbortey -->}}</ref>\n| position = [[Midfielder|Winger]]\n| currentclub = \n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = \n| years1 = 2000\n| clubs1 = [[Ghapoha Readers]]\n| caps1  = \n| goals1 = \n| years2 = 2001\u20132010\n| clubs2 = [[Accra Hearts of Oak S.C.|Hearts of Oak]]<ref>https://www.modernghana.com/sports/498669/shocker-former-ghana-star-don-bortey-reveals-he-is-38-years.html</ref>\n| years3 = 2002\u20132003\n| clubs3 = \u2192 [[Al-Wasl F.C.|Al Wasl]] (loan)\n| years4 = 2008\u20132009\n| clubs4 = \u2192 [[Bnei Sakhnin F.C.|Bnei Sakhnin]] (loan)\n| years5 = 2010\u20132013\n| clubs5 = [[Aduana Stars F.C.|Aduana Stars]]\n| years6 = 2011\u20132012\n| clubs6 = \u2192 [[S\u00f4ng Lam Ngh\u1ec7 An F.C.|S\u00f4ng Lam Ngh\u1ec7 An]] (loan)\n| years7 = 2013\n| clubs7 = [[New Edubiase United F.C.|New Edubiase United]]\n| years8 = 2014\n| clubs8 = [[The Panthers F.C.|The Panthers]]\n| years9 = 2015\n| clubs9 = [[\u00c5nge IF]]\n| years10=  2019\n| clubs10= [[Accra Great Olympics F.C.|Great Olympics]]\n| nationalyears1 = 1999\n| nationalteam1  = [[Ghana national football team|Ghana U-17]]\n| nationalcaps1  =  6\n| nationalgoals1 = 3\n| nationalyears2 = 2002\u20132004\n| nationalteam2  = [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]]\n| nationalcaps2  =  7\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n}}\n\n'''Bernard Dong-Bortey''' (born 22 September 1982) is a retired [[Ghana]]ian [[association football|footballer]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Sorteo segunda fase Copa de Su Excelencia|url=http://www.feguifut.org/index.php/Noticias/118-the-panters-se-refuerza-con-destacados-delanteros.html|publisher=www.feguifut.org|accessdate=22 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nBortey began his career 2000 with [[Ghapoha Readers]] in [[Tema]]. One year later, he moved to [[Accra Hearts of Oak SC]] and became an integral part of the \"64 Battalion\" and a deadly force alongside [[Charles Asampong Taylor]], [[Ishmael Addo]], [[Emmanuel Osei Kuffour]]. Hearts loaned him out in 2002 to [[Al Wasl FC]] in [[Dubai]], where he played for 6 months. He returned in June 2002 to Hearts where he won the league and shared the Top Scorer award with Charles Asampong Taylor.<ref>[http://www.weltfussball.de/spieler_profil/bernard-dong-bortey/ Profile @ Weltfussball]</ref> Nicknamed \"Dong Dada Diouf\" a reference to Senegalese forward [[El Hadji Diouf]] due to similar style of play and his dyed hair.\n\nSince 2015 in Sweden with [[\u00c5nge IF]], Bortey was without club until signing with Ghanian club [[Accra Great Olympics F.C.|Accra Great Olympics]] in December 2019.<ref>[https://futaa.com/article/198276/bernard-dong-bortey-signs-two-year-deal-with-great-olympics Bernard Dong Bortey signs two-year deal with Great Olympics], futaa.com, 5 December 2019</ref> However, in the beginning of January 2020, Olympics manager Prince George Koffie said, that he hadn't seen Bortey yet and therefore wasn't a part of his team.<ref>[https://footballghana.com/don-bortey-is-not-part-of-my-team-great-olympics-coach-insists Don Bortey is not part of my team - Great Olympics coach insists], footballghana.com, 8 January 2020</ref> A few days later Bortey said that he didn't receive the financial benefit's he was promised when he signed the contract and that he wouldn't play until they had paid him.<ref>[https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/SportsArchive/I-won-t-play-for-Olympics-tilI-they-pay-me-Dong-Bortey-836536 I won\u2019t play for Olympics tilI they pay me - Dong Bortey], ghanaweb.com, 13 January 2020</ref> On 6 April 2020, Bortey officially announced his retirement and expressed, that he would like to be a coach.<ref>[https://www.modernghana.com/sports/993843/bernard-dong-bortey-confirms-retirement-from-footb.html Bernard Dong Bortey Confirms Retirement From Football], modernghana.com, 6 April 2020</ref>\n\n==International career==\nBortey played twenty-seven games for the [[Ghanaian national football team]] and scored nine times; the latest game being in the qualifying stage of the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]] He also represented his homeland in the [[1999 FIFA U-17 World Championship]] in New Zealand, where he played 6 games and scored 3 goals.<ref>{{FIFA player|175530}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n* Played in the [[African Champions League]] with [[Accra Hearts of Oak SC]] in 2001.\n* Four-time Ghanaian Premier League Champion with [[Accra Hearts of Oak SC]].\n* [[CAF Confederation Cup]] winner with [[Accra Hearts of Oak SC]] in 2004.<ref>[https://dongborteyisalegend.wordpress.com/2014/11/01/bernard-dong-bortey-that-goal/]</ref>\n* Ghana Premier League joint goal-king in 2002.\n* Topscorer of the 2012 [[GHALCA Top Four]] tournament.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://sports.peacefmonline.com/news/200910/29219.php |title=GHALCA Honours Outstanding Players And Officials |access-date=2009-12-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091223041344/http://sports.peacefmonline.com/news/200910/29219.php |archive-date=2009-12-23 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/soccer/pop-up.php?ID=153 GhanaWeb Profile]\n* {{NFT player|2601}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dong-Bortey, Bernard}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Greater Accra Region]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian footballers]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Ghana international footballers]]\n[[Category:Accra Hearts of Oak S.C. players]]\n[[Category:Al-Wasl F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bnei Sakhnin F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Aduana Stars F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Song Lam Nghe An F.C. players]]\n[[Category:New Edubiase United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:The Panthers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:\u00c5nge IF players]]\n[[Category:Accra Great Olympics F.C. players]]\n[[Category:UAE Pro League players]]\n[[Category:Ghana Premier League players]]\n[[Category:2011 African Nations Championship players]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian expatriate sportspeople in Israel]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian expatriate sportspeople in Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian expatriate sportspeople in Equatorial Guinea]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian expatriate sportspeople in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Israel]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Equatorial Guinea]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name= Bernard Bortey\n| image =\n| fullname = Bernard Dong-Bortey\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1982|9|22|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Nungua]], Ghana\n| height = 1.80m<ref>{{FootballDatabase.eu|5678-bernard-dongbortey}}</ref>\n| position = [[Midfielder|Winger]]\n| currentclub =                                       \n| youthyears1 =  \n| youthclubs1 =  \n| years1 =  2000 \n| clubs1 = [[Ghapoha Readers]] \n| caps1  =     \n| goals1 = \n| years2 =  2001\u20132010 \n| clubs2 = [[Accra Hearts of Oak S.C.|Hearts of Oak]]<ref>https://www.modernghana.com/sports/498669/shocker-former-ghana-star-don-bortey-reveals-he-is-38-years.html</ref>\n| years3 =  2002\u20132003 \n| clubs3 =  \u2192 [[Al-Wasl F.C.|Al Wasl]] (loan)\n| years4 =  2008\u20132009 \n| clubs4 =  \u2192 [[Bnei Sakhnin F.C.|Bnei Sakhnin]] (loan) \n| years5 =  2010\u20132013\n| clubs5 = [[Aduana Stars F.C.|Aduana Stars]]\n| years6 =  2011\u20132012\n| clubs6 =  \u2192 [[S\u00f4ng Lam Ngh\u1ec7 An F.C.|S\u00f4ng Lam Ngh\u1ec7 An]] (loan)\n| years7 =  2013\n| clubs7 = [[New Edubiase United F.C.|New Edubiase United]]\n| years8 =  2014\n| clubs8 = [[The Panthers F.C.|The Panthers]]\n| years9 =  2015\n| clubs9 = [[\u00c5nge IF]]\n| years10=  2019\n| clubs10= [[Accra Great Olympics F.C.|Great Olympics]]\n| nationalyears1 =  1999 \n| nationalteam1  = [[Ghana national football team|Ghana U-17]] \n| nationalcaps1  =  6\n| nationalgoals1 =  3\n| nationalyears2 =  2002\u20132004\n| nationalteam2  = [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]]\n| nationalcaps2  =  7\n| nationalgoals2 =  0\n}}\n\n'''Bernard Dong-Bortey''' (born 22 September 1982) is a retired [[Ghana]]ian [[association football|footballer]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Sorteo segunda fase Copa de Su Excelencia|url=http://www.feguifut.org/index.php/Noticias/118-the-panters-se-refuerza-con-destacados-delanteros.html|publisher=www.feguifut.org|accessdate=22 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nBortey began his career 2000 with [[Ghapoha Readers]] in [[Tema]]. One year later, he moved to [[Accra Hearts of Oak SC]] and became an integral part of the \"64 Battalion\" and a deadly force alongside [[Charles Asampong Taylor]], [[Ishmael Addo]], [[Emmanuel Osei Kuffour]]. Hearts loaned him out in 2002 to [[Al Wasl FC]] in [[Dubai]], where he played for 6 months. He returned in June 2002 to Hearts where he won the league and shared the Top Scorer award with Charles Asampong Taylor.<ref>[http://www.weltfussball.de/spieler_profil/bernard-dong-bortey/ Profile @ Weltfussball]</ref> Nicknamed \"Dong Dada Diouf\" a reference to Senegalese forward [[El Hadji Diouf]] due to similar style of play and his dyed hair.\n\nSince 2015 in Sweden with [[\u00c5nge IF]], Bortey was without club until signing with Ghanian club [[Accra Great Olympics F.C.|Accra Great Olympics]] in December 2019.<ref>[https://futaa.com/article/198276/bernard-dong-bortey-signs-two-year-deal-with-great-olympics Bernard Dong Bortey signs two-year deal with Great Olympics], futaa.com, 5 December 2019</ref> However, in the beginning of January 2020, Olympics manager Prince George Koffie said, that he hadn't seen Bortey yet and therefore wasn't a part of his team.<ref>[https://footballghana.com/don-bortey-is-not-part-of-my-team-great-olympics-coach-insists Don Bortey is not part of my team - Great Olympics coach insists], footballghana.com, 8 January 2020</ref> A few days later Bortey said that he didn't receive the financial benefit's he was promised when he signed the contract and that he wouldn't play until they had paid him.<ref>[https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/SportsArchive/I-won-t-play-for-Olympics-tilI-they-pay-me-Dong-Bortey-836536 I won\u2019t play for Olympics tilI they pay me - Dong Bortey], ghanaweb.com, 13 January 2020</ref> On 6 April 2020, Bortey officially announced his retirement and expressed, that he would like to be a coach.<ref>[https://www.modernghana.com/sports/993843/bernard-dong-bortey-confirms-retirement-from-footb.html Bernard Dong Bortey Confirms Retirement From Football], modernghana.com, 6 April 2020</ref>\n\n==International career==\nBortey played twenty-seven games for the [[Ghanaian national football team]] and scored nine times; the latest game being in the qualifying stage of the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]] He also represented his homeland in the [[1999 FIFA U-17 World Championship]] in New Zealand, where he played 6 games and scored 3 goals.<ref>{{FIFA player|175530}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n* Played in the [[African Champions League]] with [[Accra Hearts of Oak SC]] in 2001.\n* Four-time Ghanaian Premier League Champion with [[Accra Hearts of Oak SC]].\n* [[CAF Confederation Cup]] winner with [[Accra Hearts of Oak SC]] in 2004.<ref>[https://dongborteyisalegend.wordpress.com/2014/11/01/bernard-dong-bortey-that-goal/]</ref>\n* Ghana Premier League joint goal-king in 2002. \n* Topscorer of the 2012 [[GHALCA Top Four]] tournament.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://sports.peacefmonline.com/news/200910/29219.php |title=GHALCA Honours Outstanding Players And Officials |access-date=2009-12-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091223041344/http://sports.peacefmonline.com/news/200910/29219.php |archive-date=2009-12-23 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/soccer/pop-up.php?ID=153 GhanaWeb Profile]\n* {{NFT player|pid=2601}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dong-Bortey, Bernard}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Greater Accra Region]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian footballers]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Ghana international footballers]]\n[[Category:Accra Hearts of Oak S.C. players]]\n[[Category:Al-Wasl F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bnei Sakhnin F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Aduana Stars F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Song Lam Nghe An F.C. players]]\n[[Category:New Edubiase United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:The Panthers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:\u00c5nge IF players]]\n[[Category:Accra Great Olympics F.C. players]]\n[[Category:UAE Pro League players]]\n[[Category:Ghana Premier League players]]\n[[Category:2011 African Nations Championship players]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian expatriate sportspeople in Israel]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian expatriate sportspeople in Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian expatriate sportspeople in Equatorial Guinea]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian expatriate sportspeople in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Israel]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Equatorial Guinea]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Sweden]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "update FootballDatabase.eu template, misc formatting", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bernard_Dong_Bortey"}
